  "prompt": "Why aren't there more apps like Word Lens?",
  "response": "Word Lens was an innovative augmented reality (AR) translation app that allowed users to instantly translate text in real-time through their smartphone camera. Google acquired the app in 2014 and integrated its technology into Google Translate. There are a few reasons why similar apps aren't as common:\n\n1. Technical Complexity\n- Real-time translation and text recognition require advanced computer vision and machine learning algorithms\n- Accurate optical character recognition (OCR) and translation are challenging to implement\n\n2. Computational Resources\n- These apps require significant processing power\n- They need to perform multiple complex tasks simultaneously (image capture, text recognition, translation)\n\n3. Language and Context Challenges\n- Translating text accurately requires understanding context and nuanced language\n- Different writing systems and scripts add complexity\n\n4. Development Cost\n- Creating such sophisticated apps is expensive and time-consuming\n- Requires expertise in multiple technological domains\n\n5. Market Limitations\n- Limited demand compared to other app categories\n- Google Translate and similar apps have dominated this niche\n\nHowever, with advancing technology, more AR translation apps are emerging, and the field continues to improve with better machine learning and computational capabilities.\n\nSome current alternatives include Google Translate, Microsoft Translator, and iTranslate, which offer similar real-time translation features.",
